# Handoff

Write or read the per-change advisory runtime handoff. This is the portable
continuity surface for fresh sessions and hosts that do not wire Slipway hooks.

## Invocation
```bash
printf '## Current Position\n...' | slipway handoff write
printf '...' | slipway handoff write --section "Next Session Focus"
slipway handoff show
slipway handoff show --brief
```

## Contract
- `slipway handoff` without a subcommand behaves as `slipway handoff write`.
- `slipway handoff write` reads the narrative from stdin. Pipe a full body to the bare form, or pipe one section body with `--section <name>`.
- Non-interactive runs with nothing piped fail loudly (no `handoff_written` line) instead of writing an empty scaffold and reporting false success; an unknown `--section` name is rejected with the valid section list.
- Write at meaningful moments: task completion, before stopping, before a review split, or when a context-pressure nudge asks for continuity.
- Read on resume with `slipway handoff show`; use `show --brief` for a bounded descriptor. An empty or all-pending handoff prints a clear notice rather than nothing.
- This surface is hook-agnostic: run write/show yourself and never assume SessionStart, PreCompact, or any host hook fired.
- The machine header is engine-owned and carries identity/freshness fields only: slug, generation, session_owner, git branch/worktree, updated_at, and staleness.
- The header must not snapshot lifecycle state, substeps, next_skill, or next_command.
- The handoff is advisory only; `slipway status` and `slipway next` remain lifecycle authority.

## Flags
- `--change <slug>`: target a specific active change.
- `write --section <name>`: update one narrative section from stdin while preserving the rest (must be a known section name).
- `show --json`: emit structured handoff data (includes `empty`/`notice` when nothing is recorded).
- `show --brief`: emit the bounded descriptor for resume/session-start use.
